\begin{abstract}

  Cleft palate and lip birth defects are heritable disorders.
  Previous genome wide association studies have identified several
  loci that are associated with facial clefting. Included among these
  studies is a large case-parent trio design for which high-throughput
  genotyping arrays were used to genotype approximately 7280
  individuals, or approximately 2400 trios.  While studies of
  transmission disequilibrium are on-going, it is not well understood
  whether the previously identified loci lie in regions of copy number
  variants or the extent of copy number dosage sensitive genes that
  contribute to clefting.  To evaluate the impact of copy number
  variants on facial clefting, we re-analyzed the Illumina genotyping
  arrays for \denovo{} copy number variants.  Our analyses reveal
  several offspring with hemizygous \denovo{} deletions in a region of
  chromosome 22 previously implicated in DiGeorge syndrome.  These
  regions were validated \via{} multiplex qPCR.  Our approach also
  identified regions on chromosomes \ldots that have not been
  previously linked to cleft palate but show a high frequency of
  \denovo{} alterations in the present study.  To identify these
  hotspots of \denovo{} recombination, we describe a simple and fast
  approach for \denovo CNV detection as an alternative to a hidden
  Markov model. Our approach appears to be more robust to noisy
  samples and genomic waves. We combine visualizations of inferred
  segmental alterations with functional annotation available from
  existing \R{} packages to focus downstream analyses.

\end{abstract}

