\section{Methods}
\label{sec:methods}

BeadStudio was used to process the raw intensities for 7599 samples,
including 318 HapMap samples that were processed simultaneously by the
CIDR genotyping core. Quality control of samples for CNV analysis was
assessed primarily through the median absolute deviation (MAD) of the
log R ratios estimated for each sample across chromosomes 1 through
22.  We stratified variance estimates of the log R ratio by plate and
DNA source to assess the impact of experimental and technological
sources of variance that can give rise to batch effects
\citep{Leek2010}.

% denovo is not modeled as a hidden state.
%
Regions of \denovo{} CNV were inferred by two approaches. The first
approach we applied was a HMM for case-parent trios implemented in the
PennCNV software, referred to as the joint HMM.  The joint HMM
incorporates signal intensities from the log R ratio ($r$) and the B
allele frequency ($b$) from the father-mother-offspring trio.  An
indicator variable for the \denovo{} event status of the offspring
allows for non-Mendelian patterns of inheritance. Conditional on the
underlying hidden states $z$, the likelihood for the distribution of
the trios can be factored as a mixture of a multivariate normal
distribution for the $r's$ and a truncated multivariate normal for the
$b's$.

